// Section 2: Materials

= Materials

Every material used in this project is discussed below with its historical
basis, specific period evidence, and — where modern substitutions are made —
a comparative analysis explaining the deviation and its justification.

== The Plate: Copper

=== Historical Material

Copper was the universal plate material for intaglio engraving from the 1430s
through the end of the period and beyond. It was chosen because it is soft
enough to cut cleanly with hand tools, hard enough to hold fine detail, does
not rust, and can produce many impressions before wearing. Period copper
plate was produced by hammering ingots or sheet to the desired thickness and
then polishing to a mirror finish. Landau and Parshall's chapter on the
beginnings of engraving documents copper as the standard substrate of the
fifteenth-century intaglio shops, chosen for its combination of workability
under hand tools and resistance to corrosion @landau-parshall, and Hind
gives the same account in the opening chapters of his _History of Engraving
and Etching_ @hind-history-engraving.

=== Period vs. Modern Copper

Period copper plate was hammered, not rolled. Modern commercially available
copper sheet is cold-rolled, producing a uniform grain structure that
differs from the work-hardened pattern of period hammered plate. Landau and
Parshall's study of late-15th- and early-16th-century intaglio practice
documents the production and preparation of period copper plates by the
goldsmith-engravers of the Upper Rhine in detail, noting that hammered
plate was the universal substrate of the early intaglio shops
@landau-parshall. Hind's _History of Engraving and Etching_ gives the same
account in chs. I–II @hind-history-engraving.

=== Decision

For this project, the copper plate is hand-hammered from copper sheet and
polished to a mirror finish, replicating the period preparation method. If
modern cold-rolled copper sheet is used as a starting point, this
substitution is justified by availability and cost — the functional
difference is in grain structure only, and the rolled sheet can be further
worked with a planishing hammer to approximate hammered plate. The material
itself (copper) is identical to the period material.

== Tool Steel: Gravers

=== Historical Material

Period gravers were made from high-carbon steel, hardened and tempered by the
engraver or a toolsmith. Theophilus Presbyter's _De Diversis Artibus_
(c. 1100–1120), the oldest surviving complete treatise on metalworking
crafts, describes the making and heat treatment of the full array of the
goldsmith's steel bench tools in Book III, including a dedicated chapter
(ch. XIV, "De Ferris Incisoriis" / "Of Cutting Instruments") on the hand-held
cutting irons with which "gold is cut, and silver, or thick copper":

#quote(block: true)[
  Cutting instruments are also made broad and even, of such a size that they
  may be held in the whole hand, and that they may rise above the hand: they
  even extend below the hand broad, thin and sharp. Many of these are made
  large and small; with these gold is cut, and silver, or thick copper.
]

(Theophilus, _De Diversis Artibus_, Book III, ch. XIV, "Of Cutting
Instruments," Hendrie 1847 translation @theophilus-hendrie.) A few chapters
later, on the making of files — close relatives of the graver, also forged
from high-carbon steel, hardened by quenching, and finished with cut teeth —
Theophilus is explicit that the stock material must be the highest grade of
steel available to a medieval workshop:

#quote(block: true)[
  Files are made from pure steel, large and moderately sized, triangular and
  round. Others also are made which are stronger in the middle, from soft
  iron inside, but outwardly they are covered with steel.
]

(Theophilus, _De Diversis Artibus_, Book III, ch. XVII, "Of Files," Hendrie
1847 translation @theophilus-hendrie.) The same "pure steel" standard
documented here for files applies across the small hand tools of the
goldsmith's bench that Book III describes — including the cutting irons of
ch. XIV and the grooving irons of ch. XX, all forged from the same high-grade
stock. Commercially available gravers in the period would have been forged
from bloomery or crucible steel with a carbon content sufficient to harden
by quenching — roughly equivalent to modern W-1 (water hardening) or O-1
(oil hardening) tool steel, which are plain high-carbon steels @theophilus.

=== Comparative Analysis: A2 Tool Steel vs. Period Steel

This project uses 3/16-inch (4.8 mm) square A2 tool steel bar stock — an
air-hardening tool steel — shaped by a hybrid workflow: light forging on
the tang end to start a slight taper, followed by stock removal (grinding,
filing, sanding) to finish the cross-section, point geometry, and tang
profile. This avoids the more demanding work of forging the full
cross-section down from a larger bar while still using the period operation
of hot-tapering the tang. A2 differs from period carbon steel in that it contains
chromium and molybdenum additions that allow it to harden in air rather
than requiring a liquid quench. The
functional result — a hardened steel cutting tool at approximately
Rockwell C 58–62 — is identical. The advantages of A2 for this application
are: reduced risk of quench cracking on the thin cross-sections of gravers;
minimal distortion during heat treatment; and the engraver's existing
familiarity with the material from prior toolmaking experience (chasing
chisels and repoussé punches).

The substitution is justified on practical grounds: the cutting performance,
hardness, and edge-holding characteristics are functionally equivalent to
period carbon steel. The tool's behavior under the burin is functionally
equivalent to a period graver for cutting copper at this hardness range; the
differences in chip behavior between A2's alloyed steel and a plain-carbon
period blade are subtle and would only matter for the most demanding fine-line
work. For maximum period authenticity, O-1 or W-1 tool steel
could be used instead, as these are plain carbon steels closer in composition
to period bloomery steel, requiring oil or water quench respectively. Old
file steel is another documented traditional source material that closely
approximates period carbon steel. Experienced engravers report making
functional gravers from O-1, W-1, drill rod, and old file steel, all of
which are plain high-carbon steels @engraverscafe-homemade
@engraverscafe-my-own.

== Graver Handles: Dense Hardwood

=== Historical Material

The traditional material for graver handles is a dense, fine-grained
hardwood that does not split under the tang and does not deform under the
heel of the palm. Modern reference works on the burin name boxwood
(_Buxus sempervirens_) as the species most often used in surviving and
contemporary handles, though the period treatises that describe the burin
in detail rarely specify the wood. Bosse, in his 1645 _Traicté_, refers
only to a "bois ferme & non sujet à s'esclatter" — a firm wood not prone to
splitting — when he describes fitting handles to small engraving tools
@bosse-traite, and Theophilus, in Book III of _De Diversis Artibus_,
describes the cutting irons of the goldsmith's bench as "fitted in their
handles" without naming the species @theophilus-hendrie. The shape, by
contrast, is well-attested across both period and modern descriptions:
the handle is mushroom-shaped with one side cut flat, approximately
1.5–2 inches (4–5 cm) in length, providing an ergonomic palm grip that
positions the shaft low to the work surface. The 1911 _Encyclopædia
Britannica_'s entry on Line-Engraving describes the burin as fitted with
"a handle rather like a mushroom with one side cut away"
@britannica1911-line-engraving.

=== Decision

Handles for this project are turned on a lathe from cherry (_Prunus_ sp.).
Cherry is dense, fine-grained, and resistant to splitting under the tang —
meeting Bosse's _"bois ferme & non sujet à s'esclatter"_ criterion exactly.
Cherry and other European fruitwoods (pear, apple, plum) were standard
period turnery materials in fifteenth- and sixteenth-century European
workshops, used widely for small tool handles, instrument parts, and
printing blocks; they are functionally equivalent to boxwood for this
application, with the same density range and resistance to splitting. At
the time of this writing, the first cherry-wood handle has been completed;
each graver will have its own dedicated handle with the tang burned into a
drilled starter hole — no ferrule, no set screw, no glue. The burning-in
method (heating the tang to a low red and pressing it into the wood, so
the steel scorches the wood to its own exact profile) is the traditional
pre-modern fit for small steel hand tools and is described in §3.1.4. This
replicates the documented period practice in which engravers maintained a
set of individually handled tools.

== Sharpening Stones

=== Historical Material

Period European engravers sharpened on locally available natural hones —
fine-grained sandstones, slates, and schistose oilstones quarried in the
Rhineland, the Vosges, the Italian Alps, and other European sources. A
leather strop dressed with abrasive powder (rouge or tripoli) was used for
final polishing. The general workflow — coarse stone, then finer stone,
then leather strop — has been continuous from the period to the present,
even as the specific stone sources have changed.

=== Decision and Substitution

This project uses synthetic Japanese waterstones in a 1000 / 4000 / 8000
grit progression, finished with a leather strop dressed with chromium-oxide
polishing compound. *Synthetic waterstones are a substitution.* Modern
synthetic waterstones — bonded aluminum-oxide or silicon-carbide abrasives
in a friable resin matrix — were not available to a 15th- or 16th-century
European engraver, who would have used local natural hones of the kinds
described above. Waterstones cut faster than natural hones, expose fresh
abrasive as they wear, and are available at extremely fine grits (8000 and
above) that produce a polish equivalent to the finest natural novaculite or
period European hone. For burin work specifically, the leather strop with
chromium-oxide compound is what brings the cutting edge to its final mirror
polish, and that final step is the same regardless of which stones precede
it. The functional result — a mirror-polished face and heel on a burin
sharp enough to lift a clean copper curl — is the same edge a period
engraver would have achieved with their own local stones and strop.
Ganoksin describes the modern workflow, which mirrors the period sequence:
"Grinding is usually done on an oilstone, working in a circular stroke,
first on a coarse stone and then on a finer one. […] Follow this with a
few strokes on a hard leather with a polishing powder to create a mirror
bright finish" @ganoksin-engraving-tools. No diamond plates, ceramic
stones, or powered sharpening systems are used.

== Design Transfer Medium

=== Historical Method

Period engravers transferred designs by tracing from a paper drawing using a
stylus. The transfer medium was a dark or colored powder applied to the back
of the drawing, which left faint guide lines on the plate when traced over
with a pointed tool. Abraham Bosse, in his 1645 _Traicté_, devotes a chapter
("Manière de s'apprester pour desseigner, contre tirer ou calquer son dessein
sur la planche") to exactly this operation, describing two equivalent
arrangements: the drawing is either rubbed directly on its reverse with
powder, or laid over a separate sheet of paper prepared with powder, then
fixed to the plate with soft wax and traced over with a "pointe à calquer"
so that the contours of the design are transferred onto the plate below
@bosse-traite. Bosse writes of the drawing
"on bon papier" whose verso is "rougy […] en respandant dessus et la frottant
avec un petit linge, en sorte qu'il soit bien également rouge par tout" —
uniformly reddened with powdered sanguine — and then of passing the calquing
point "sur tous les contours des figures qui le composent, en l'appuyant
assez fort et également […] et cela fait vous devez sçavoir que tous les
contours de vostre dessein […] seront marquez empraints ou calquez […] de la
planche." Bosse's method uses sanguine (powdered red chalk), but the
technique is the same back-of-the-drawing transfer that survives in
workshop practice, substituting lamp-black soot for the red powder when a
dark line on a bright polished surface is preferred.

=== Decision

Lamp black (soot from a candle or oil lamp) rubbed onto the back of the
reversed drawing, then traced with a steel stylus. Modern carbon paper is a
functional equivalent but not strictly period; lamp black transfer is the
documented period method and is used for this project.

== Ink and Paper (If Printing)

If paper impressions are pulled from the finished plate: period printing ink
was oil-based, made from lampblack ground in linseed oil. Period paper was
handmade laid paper (showing chain lines and laid lines from the papermaking
mould), dampened before printing. Wove paper was not invented until the 18th
century and would be anachronistic. Modern handmade laid paper is available
from specialty suppliers and is functionally identical to period paper.
